Author: cptartur
Content: It's a hash od contract that is declared: starknet distinguishes between contract declaration and deployment. Declaring contract is kind of like writing a `class Contract` declaration in java and deployment is actually make an instance of contract like `new Contract()`

Author: cptartur
Content: I recommend you read this first https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/intro.html and perhaps other parts of the docs

Author: cptartur
Content: There's also an instruction there how to declare contracts through a CLI, starknet-jvm doesn't currently support calculating class hash, so you'd have to use some other tool to calculate it  if you want to make `Declare` or `DeployAccount` transactions in java.

Author: JakubPtak#8889
Content: You create invoke tx directly. Since some time all transactions must go through an account contract. This means that the only entry point selector that makes sense is the `execute` one. I strongly suggest you to use StandardAccount that hides all those details. I see that you need a custom signature - you can create a custom `Signer ` that will return your hardcoded parameters.

Author: JakubPtak#8889
Content: So every call you make within a tx is in fact transformed into calldata array provided to execute method of an account.

Content:
If you want to create an openzeppelin account (using already declared openzeppelin contract), and not declare an account contract, you should use `provider.deployAccount` instead:
https://github.com/software-mansion/starknet-jvm/blob/main/lib/src/main/kotlin/com/swmansion/starknet/provider/Provider.kt#L348
You can get class hash for openzeppelin contract on starkscan depending on which net you want to use:
https://testnet.starkscan.co/address-book
https://testnet-2.starkscan.co/address-book
https://starkscan.co/address-book
